xperts%20we%20consulted%20recommended%20listening%20at%20a%20low%20volume%20and%20using%20a%20sleep%20timer%20to%20minimize%20exposure%20to%20noise%20throughout%20the%20night.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Ch3%3ECan%20I%20use%20regular%20headphones%20for%20sleeping%3F%3C%2Fh3%3E%3Cp%3ETheoretically%2C%20yes%2C%20but%20experts%20recommend%20consulting%20a%20doctor%20or%20sleep%20specialist%20to%20confirm%20the%20use%20of%20your%20specific%20pair%20of%20headphones%20for%20regular%20use.%20Much%20like%20sleep%20headphones%2C%20a%20low%20volume%20and%20limited%20listening%20time%20are%20recommended%2C%20and%20it%20use%20advisable%20to%20avoid%20using%20a%20corded%20pair%20that%20could%20lead%20to%20accidental%20strangulation.%20Winter%20also%20notes%20that%20regular%20headphones%20can%20become%20uncomfortable%20or%20painful%20when%20used%20for%20extended%20periods.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Ch3%3EAre%20sleep%20headphones%20good%20for%20side%20sleepers%3F%3C%2Fh3%3E%3Cp%3EMany%20sleep%20headphones%20are%20well-suited%20for%20side%20sleepers%2C%20especially%20those%20with%20flat%20or%20headband-style%20designs.%20Look%20for%20products%20specifically%20labeled%20for%20side%20sleepers%2C%20and%20keep%20in%20mind%20that%20no%20pair%20is%20one-size-fits-all.%20Both%20Dr.%20Tate%20and%20licensed%20psychologist%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fuptownpsychologyny.com%2Four-team%2Fanne-josephson%2F%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3EAnne%20Josephson%3C%2Fa%3E%20recommend%20an%20on-ear%20pair%20(such%20as%20a%20headband)%20over%20in-ear%20headphones%20for%20side%20sleepers%2C%20as%20this%20will%20not%20add%20any%20internal%20pressure%20between%20the%20ear%20and%20the%20pillow.%20Winter%20recommends%20being%20mindful%20about%20selecting%20a%20comfortable%20pillow%20for%20side%20sleeping%2C%20and%20if%20you%20often%20sleep%20on%20the%20same%20side%2C%20he%20suggests%20using%20only%20one%20earbud%20(inside%20the%20ear%20that's%20not%20resting%20on%20the%20pillow).%3C%2Fp%3E%3Ch3%3EDo%20sleep%20headphones%20block%20snoring%20or%20other%20noise%3F%3C%2Fh3%3E%3Cp%3EYes%2C%20especially%20those%20with%20good%20passive%20noise%20blocking.%20Across%20the%20board%2C%20Winter%20notes%20that%20sleep%20headphones%20are%20typically%20useful%20for%20blocking%20out%20lower-frequency%20sounds%20like%20snoring.%20White%20noise%20may%20also%20help%20with%20snoring%2C%20and%20sleep%20headphones%20should%20not%20block%20important%20noises%2C%20such%20as%20a%20fire%20alarm%20or%20a%20loud%20knock%20on%20the%20door.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Ch3%3EHow%20loud%20should%20music%20be%3F%3C%2Fh3%3E%3Cp%3EWhile%20the%20experts%20we%20consulted%20did%20not%20recommend%20a%20specific%20metric%2C%20all%20four%20unanimously%20agreed%20that%20a%20lower%20volume%20is%20best%20for%20sleep%20hygiene%20and%20ear%20health.%20Robinson%20suggests%20a%20volume%20that's%20just%20high%20enough%20to%20shift%20focus%20into%20sleeping%20but%20no%20louder%20than%20necessary.%20Winter%20recommends%20trying%20your%20best%20to%20sleep%20in%20silence%20at%20first%2C%20and%20if%20you%20use%20headphones%2C%20to%20use%20them%20at%20the%20quietest%20volume%20possible.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Ch3%3EWhat%20sounds%20are%20best%20for%20sleep%3F%3C%2Fh3%3E%3Cp%3EAccording%20to%20Tate%2C%20the%20more%20%26quot%3Bboring%26quot%3B%20a%20sound%20may%20be%2C%20the%20better%20it%20is%20to%20fall%20asleep%20to%2C%20as%20a%20change%20in%20pitch%20or%20volume%20could%20kick%20you%20out%20of%20a%20deep%20sleep.%20Tate%2C%20Robinson%2C%20and%20Winter%20all%20recommend%20white%20noise%2C%20while%20Tate%20and%20Robinson%20additionally%20recommend%20brown%20noise%20and%20pink%20noise%20(all%20named%20after%20their%20frequency).%20Both%20Robinson%20and%20Josephson%20suggest%20noises%20that%20mimic%20nature.%20If%20music%20or%20a%20podcast%20is%20preferred%2C%20Tate%20encourages%20monotone%20voices%20and%20calming%20sounds.%20Winter%20strongly%20discourages%20dialogue%20or%20repeating%20sounds%2C%20as%20our%20brains%20are%20more%20likely%20to%20focus%20on%20these%20than%20